Pakistan's [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] agency (ISI) has been heavily involved in India, with one of the subsections of its Joint Intelligence Bureau department completely devoted to operations against India.<ref name="FAS">{{cite web | url = http://www.fas.org/irp/world/pakistan/isi/ | title = Directorate for Inter-Services Intelligence  | publisher = [[Federation of American Scientists]] | author = Pike, John | date = 25 July 2002 | accessdate= 25 June 2012 | authorlink = John E. Pike }}</ref> The Joint Signal Intelligence Bureau department has been also supporting [[Kashmir|Kashmiri]] militants in regards to communication.<ref name="FAS"/> The Joint Intelligence North section of the Joint Counter-Intelligence Bureau wing deals exclusively with India.<ref name="Daily">{{cite web | url = http://www.fas.org/irp/world/pakistan/isi/india.html | title = Daily Describes Activities of ISI in India |work=[[The Pioneer]] | publisher = [[Federation of American Scientists]] | date = 30 June 1999 | accessdate= 25 June 2012}}</ref> In the 1950s the ISI's Covert Action Division supplied arms to [[Insurgency in Northeast India|insurgents]] in [[Northeast India]].<ref name="FAS"/><ref name="South Asia Analysis Group >{{cite web|url=http://www.acsa.net/isi/index.html|title=PAKISTAN'S INTER-SERVICES INTELLIGENCE (ISI)| accessdate= 25 June 2012|first=B|last=Raman}}</ref> India has also accused the ISI of reinvigorating terrorism in the country via support to the pro-Khalistan militant groups such as [[International Sikh Youth Federation]], in order to take revenge against India for its help in creation of [[Bangladesh]] as well as to destabilize the Indian State.<ref name=SATPISYF>{{cite web|url=http://www.satp.org/satporgtp/countries/india/states/punjab/terrorist_outfits/ISYF.htm|title=International Sikh Youth Federation (ISYF) South Asia Terrorism Portal article|publisher=The Institute for Conflict Management | accessdate= 25 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="Shah1997">{{cite book|author=Mehtab Ali Shah|title=The foreign policy of Pakistan: ethnic impacts on diplomacy, 1971-1994|year=1997|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-86064-169-5|pages=149<U+2013>}}</ref> A report by India's [[Intelligence Bureau (India)|Intelligence Bureau]] indicated that ISI was "desperately trying to revive Sikh" militant activity in India.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2008/jun/10vicky.htm|title=200 Pak organisations raise funds for terror: IB|last=Nanjappa|first=Vicky|date=10 June 2008|publisher=Rediff.com|language=Englilsh| accessdate= 25 June 2012}}</ref> The ISI is also active in printing and supplying [[Counterfeit money|counterfeit]] [[Indian rupee]] notes.<ref name="Chitkara2003">{{cite book|author=M. G. Chitkara|title=Combating Terrorism|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3A0DG8caV6AC&pg=PA296|accessdate=25 June 2012|date=1 January 2003|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-7648-415-2|page=296}}</ref>

==Operations in Jammu and Kashmir==
About [[Pakistani rupee|Rs.]] 2.4 [[crore]] are paid out per month by the ISI, in order to fund its activities in [[Jammu and Kashmir]].<ref name="FAS"/> Pro-Pakistani groups were reportedly favored over other militant groups.<ref name=FAS/> Creation of six militant groups in Kashmir, which included [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]] (LeT), was aided by the ISI.<ref name=Salon>[http://www.salon.com/opinion/feature/2008/12/12/pakistan/index.html Does Obama understand his biggest foreign-policy challenge?], [[Salon.com]], 2008-12-12</ref><ref name=NYT1>[http://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/01/world/asia/01pstan.html Pakistani Militants Admit Role in Siege, Official Says], [[The New York Times]], 2009-01-01</ref> According to American Intelligence officials, ISI is still providing protection and help to LeT.<ref name=NYT1/> The [[Pakistan Army]] and ISI also LeT volunteers to surreptitiously penetrate from [[Pakistan Administrated Kashmir]] to Jammu and Kashmir.<ref name="tellis2010">{{Cite news| title = Bad Company <U+2013> Lashkar-e-Tayyiba and the Growing Ambition of Islamist Militancy in Pakistan| url = http://www.internationalrelations.house.gov/111/tel031110.pdf| format = PDF| date = 11 March 2010| author = Ashley J. Tellis| publisher = Carnegie Endowment for International Peace}}</ref> As of 2010, the degree of control that ISI retains over LeT<U+2019>s operations is not known.<ref name='lisacurtis2010'>{{Cite document | first = Lisa | last = Curtis | contribution = Bad Company: Lashkar-e-Tayyiba and the Growing Ambition of Islamist Militancy in Pakistan | title = Testimony to US Congress Committee on Foreign Affairs | place = Washington, DC | date = 2010-03-11}}</ref> The LeT was also reported to have been directed by the [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI) to widen its network in the Jammu region where a considerable section of the populace comprised Punjabis.<ref>[http://www.eyespymag.com/terrorgroupsL-M.htm Lashkar-e-Taiba],''Eyespymag''</ref>

==Involvement with 26/11 attacks==
[[Zabiuddin Ansari]], a Lashkar-e-Taiba militant accused for his involvement in the [[2008 Mumbai attacks]], said that ISI and [[Pakistani army]] officials were involved in planning the attacks and had attended the meetings.<ref name=TOI_Saudi_help>{{cite news|title=Saudis helped India nab 26/11 handler Abu Jundal|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Saudis-helped-India-nab-26/11-handler-Abu-Jundal/articleshow/14396009.cms|accessdate=25 June 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=25 June 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/68hCOOW5G|archivedate=2012-06-25|}}</ref>

